<!--
    Demo Party 03 - Person Witness on case 04 (Pending General Inquiry)
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the THIRD of the 8-party demo dataset; it is the SOLE
    party on case 04 (which is in Pending status awaiting external info
    per pending_reason=Awaiting Info), demonstrating the single-party
    pattern on the General Inquiry flow path. Together with parties 01,
    02, and 04 through 08, this record satisfies AAP Section 0.4.1's
    seed-data folder requirements for `seed-data/parties/`.

    The complete 8-party fixture matrix (per the agent prompt's
    "Key Insights" Section 1):

        Party 01 - Person      / Requester  / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Party 02 - Organization/ Respondent / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Party 03 - Person      / Witness    / parent case 04 (Pending GI)  ## THIS FILE
        Party 04 - Person      / Requester  / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Party 05 - Organization/ Respondent / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Party 06 - Person      / Requester  / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Party 07 - Organization/ Respondent / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Party 08 - Person      / Witness    / parent case 09 (Resolved Complaint)

    The 8-party dataset thus exercises:
      * All 2 `party_type` choice values (Person x5, Organization x3) -
        this party contributes the THIRD of the five Person entries.
        The Person branch demonstrates that the conditional UI Policy
        at ../../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml
        correctly shows the <person> reference field and HIDES the
        <organization> reference field when party_type=Person.
      * All 3 example `role_label` values (Requester x3, Respondent x3,
        Witness x2) - this party contributes the FIRST of the two
        Witness entries (the other Witness is party 08 on case 09). The
        Witness role demonstrates the THIRD AAP-Section-0.5.7 example
        role (alongside Requester on parties 01, 04, 06 and Respondent
        on parties 02, 05, 07). Semantically the witness is a third-
        party observer whose information is needed by the case agent;
        when this party row exists on a Pending case awaiting info,
        the implication is that the agent has identified the witness
        but is still gathering the witness's testimony - hence the
        case sits in Pending state pending external input.
      * 5 unique parent cases (03, 04, 05, 08, 09) - this party is the
        SOLE party on case 04; while cases 03, 05, and 08 each have
        TWO parties (Person + Organization) demonstrating the dual-
        party pattern, this party alone demonstrates the SINGLE-PARTY
        pattern on the General Inquiry flow (mirroring party 08's
        single-party pattern on the Complaint flow's case 09).
      * Both flow paths (General Inquiry: cases 03, 04, 05 / Complaint:
        cases 08, 09) - this party tests the polymorphic Person branch
        on the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's Pending case; party 08 (Person
        Witness on case 09) tests the same on the Complaint flow's
        Resolved case. Together these two Person/Witness rows on
        different lifecycle phases prove the Witness role works on
        both flow paths and at different states.
      * All 3 demo users as `person` references (manager x2, agent x3,
        viewer x1) - this party contributes the FIRST of three demo
        agent entries (the others are parties 06 and 08). The demo
        agent is the most-frequently referenced demo user across the
        seed-data fixture and appears as the person on parties 03,
        06, and 08; on the assigned_agent slot of every In Progress
        and Resolved case; and on the assigned_to slot of every demo
        task. This pattern reflects the agent's role as the primary
        case worker who handles end-to-end case progression.

    Lifecycle position - WHY Person / Witness / parent Pending General
    Inquiry case is meaningful:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.7 the case_party schema is:
          case        - Reference -> x_[scope]_case (mandatory)
          party_type  - Choice (Person | Organization, mandatory)
          person      - Reference -> sys_user (conditional: required
                        if party_type=Person)
          organization- Reference -> core_company (conditional: required
                        if party_type=Organization)
          role_label  - String(100) (mandatory; example values
                        Requester, Respondent, Witness)

      With party_type=Person, the conditional UI Policy at
      ../../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml
      activates the Person branch:
          - Show + require <person> field (populated below with
            x_[scope]_demo_agent)
          - Hide <organization> field (left empty below; the empty
            <organization/> element preserves the dictionary entry's
            existence while signaling no value)

      Case 04 is in Pending status on the General Inquiry flow per
      ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_04.xml. The case was opened by an
      external requester submitting a General Inquiry; the demo team's
      queue accepted it, the manager assigned the demo agent, the
      agent began work on it, and then the case was moved to Pending
      because the agent needed external information from a witness
      to continue. The case's pending_reason field is set to
      "Awaiting Info" per the case file. While in Pending status,
      no work progresses on the case but the agent has identified
      the witness whose information is awaited - that witness is
      represented by THIS party row. The <role_label>Witness</role_
      label> on this party records the demo agent (synthetically
      reused as the witness) as the third-party observer whose
      information is needed; once the witness provides info, the
      case can transition Pending -> In Progress (clearing the
      pending_reason via the clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress
      business rule) and then progress to Resolved. This party's
      mere existence on a Pending case is the canonical fixture
      that exercises the "Pending awaiting witness" semantics.

      Note: the AAP Section 0.5.7 example role_label values are
      Requester, Respondent, Witness; this party uses Witness as the
      THIRD example value, completing the role-label triad alongside
      party 01 (Requester on case 03) and party 02 (Respondent on
      case 03), and ensuring the demo dataset exercises every example
      value and validates that the dictionary entry's String(100)
      constraint accepts arbitrary mandatory text.

    Role / cross-dependency context (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This party DEPENDS ON (loaded BEFORE this record):
        - The scoped application records under ../../app/
            (sys_app and sys_scope; this party's <sys_scope>/<sys_
             package> reference fields resolve via the source attribute
             against those records)
        - The case_party table definition at
            ../../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml
            (this record's <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case_party</sys_
             class_name> requires the table to exist)
        - All dictionary entries for the case_party table under
            ../../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml  (every populated
             field below requires its dictionary entry to be present;
             specifically case, party_type, person, organization, and
             role_label dictionary entries)
        - The choice record for party_type at
            ../../choices/sys_choice_case_party_party_type.xml
            (the Person choice value must be registered before this
             record's <party_type>Person</party_type> can be accepted)
        - The UI Policy at
            ../../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml
            (this record's Person branch activates the policy's show-
             person/hide-organization rule at form-render time)
        - The role records under ../../roles/  (the demo agent's
             assigned-only access requires the x_[scope]_case_agent
             role and its case_party-table ACLs; the demo manager's
             full access requires the x_[scope]_case_manager role)
        - The ACL records under ../../acl/ for case_party (table-level
             read/write/create/delete ACLs gate access; the case-agent's
             "Assigned only" condition resolves through the parent
             case's assigned_agent / assigned_group)
        - ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml  (referenced by
             <person>; resolved by user_name lookup; the demo agent's
             user record must exist before this party can reference it)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_04.xml  (referenced by <case>;
             resolved by number lookup; this is the parent Pending
             General Inquiry case whose sole party this record represents)

      This party IS REFERENCED BY (loaded AFTER this record):
        - Case 04's auto-generated parties Related List (the case form
            renders a Related List of all x_[scope]_case_party records
            where <case> = current case; this party is the sole row in
            that Related List for case 04; the demo agent and demo
            manager can both see this row through the case_manager and
            case_agent ACLs)
        - The polymorphic UI Policy verification (Validation Gate 1
            per AAP Section 0.7.3): with party_type=Person, the policy
            must SHOW the <person> field's value (x_[scope]_demo_agent)
            and HIDE the <organization> slot. This party is one of the
            5 rows that exercises the Person branch of the polymorphism
            (parties 01, 03, 04, 06, 08).
        - No Flow Designer flow references this record directly;
            case_party rows are pure metadata observed by the form UI
            and audit reports, not transition gates. The state machine
            in ../../flows/{general_inquiry,complaint}_state_machine.xml
            does not query x_[scope]_case_party as part of any
            transition validation. In particular, case 04's Pending
            state is sustained by the case's own pending_reason field,
            NOT by the existence or absence of any case_party row.
        - No dashboard report queries the case_party table directly
            (per AAP Section 0.4.1 the eight reports under ../../reports/
            target x_[scope]_case and x_[scope]_case_task only); this
            party is not aggregated by any dashboard widget.

      Update Set ordering (per AAP Section 0.5.2):
        - This record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            * The scoped application records under ../../app/
            * The case_party table at ../../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml
            * All dictionary entries under ../../dictionary/
              x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml
            * The choice record sys_choice_case_party_party_type.xml
            * The demo agent user record at
              ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml  (person
              resolves by user_name lookup)
            * The parent case at
              ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_04.xml  (case field resolves
              by number lookup; that case must exist before this party
              can reference it)
            * Any role and ACL records that gate read/write access at
              import time
        - This record can be loaded BEFORE or AFTER its sibling party
          records (01, 02, 04 through 08) since they are mutually
          independent (each party's only outbound references are to
          a case, a user, and a company - never to other parties).
        - No other Update Set record depends on this party; nothing
          loaded after this party requires it as a prerequisite.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's ten authoring rules):

      Rule 1 - Synthetic only (AAP Section 0.7.2 NO-PII clause):
        person     = "x_[scope]_demo_agent"  (the synthetic demo user
                     authored at ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml;
                     no real user identity, no real email address, no
                     real name; the user_name itself is a scoped
                     synthetic identifier with the literal "[scope]"
                     placeholder)
        role_label = "Witness"  (a generic English noun describing a
                     third-party observer role; not a real person's
                     name, not an organizational identifier; one of
                     the three example role_label values enumerated
                     in AAP Section 0.5.7)
        organization = EMPTY  (no organization is associated with this
                     party because party_type=Person; the empty
                     <organization/> element preserves the dictionary
                     entry binding while explicitly signaling no value)
        NO requester email, phone, address, SSN, or other PII-bearing
        fields are populated; the case_party schema does not include
        any free-text PII slots.

      Rule 2 - Choice value precision:
        party_type = "Person"  (exactly as registered in
                     ../../choices/sys_choice_case_party_party_type.xml;
                     the FIRST of the two party-type choice values -
                     Person, Organization; capital P deliberate -
                     "Person" not "person" or "PERSON"; THIS VALUE IS
                     LOAD-BEARING because the conditional UI Policy
                     at ../../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_
                     conditional_fields.xml branches on case-sensitive
                     equality with "Person"; a typo would break the
                     polymorphic field-visibility rule)
        role_label = "Witness"  (the Title Case form, exact, per AAP
                     Section 0.5.7 example values; a free-form String
                     (100) per the schema, but the canonical example
                     values in the AAP are Requester, Respondent,
                     Witness; this record uses the Witness value to
                     contribute to the role-label triad covered by
                     the 8-party fixture)

      Rule 3 - Conditional Field Rule (the polymorphic invariant):
        With party_type=Person, the UI Policy mandates:
          * <person> populated with a sys_user reference  (DONE BELOW:
            x_[scope]_demo_agent resolved by user_name lookup)
          * <organization> empty  (DONE BELOW: empty <organization/>
            element)
        The inverse pattern is exercised by parties 02, 05, and 07
        (party_type=Organization, organization populated, person
        empty). This file is one of the five Person-branch rows
        (parties 01, 03, 04, 06, 08) that establish the canonical
        Person-branch invariant; party 03 specifically demonstrates
        the Person-branch pattern on a single-party Pending case.

      Rule 4 - Reference resolution by stable human-readable key (AAP
              Section 0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals anywhere"):
        case   : <case display_value="CASE0000004">CASE0000004</case>
                 resolves to demo case 04 by the case table's
                 idempotent number lookup. CASE0000004 is the auto-
                 numbered value the platform generates for demo case 04
                 since cases 01 through 04 import in order with the
                 CASE0000001-format auto-number counter (case 01 ->
                 CASE0000001, case 02 -> CASE0000002, case 03 ->
                 CASE0000003, case 04 -> CASE0000004). This party's
                 parent therefore resolves to the demo case 04 record
                 at ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_04.xml.
        person : <person display_value="x_[scope]_demo_agent">
                 x_[scope]_demo_agent</person>  resolves to the demo
                 agent user by the sys_user table's user_name lookup.
                 The demo agent is the most-frequently referenced demo
                 user across the seed-data fixture and appears as the
                 person on parties 03, 06, and 08; on the assigned_
                 agent slot of every In Progress and Resolved case;
                 and on the assigned_to slot of every demo task. This
                 pattern reflects the agent's role as the primary
                 case worker who handles end-to-end case progression.

        Both cross-reference fields use the display_value attribute
        AND the element text content set to the same human-readable
        key. ServiceNow's Update Set engine resolves the target sys_id
        from this key at import time via the table's idempotent-key
        lookup. NO sys_id literals appear in any cross-reference
        slot per AAP Section 0.7.2.

      Rule 5 - All mandatory case_party fields populated:
        case        - mandatory parent reference - CASE0000004
        party_type  - mandatory Choice           - "Person"
        person      - conditional Reference (required when
                      party_type=Person)         - x_[scope]_demo_agent
        organization- conditional Reference (NOT required when
                      party_type=Person)         - EMPTY (correct)
        role_label  - mandatory String(100)      - "Witness"
        Per AAP Section 0.5.7 case_party schema, this record populates
        every mandatory field for the Person branch and leaves only
        the organization slot empty (which is correct for Person
        rows). The conditional invariant is satisfied.

      Rule 6 - Scope binding:
        <sys_scope>   binds this party row to the scoped application
                      via the scope source name "x_[scope]" defined in
                      ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml at
                      <source>x_[scope]</source>; the display_value
                      "Case Management" matches the sys_app's human-
                      readable name.
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the additional
                      source="x_[scope]" attribute that is required by
                      the Update Set engine for scope-package binding.
        Note: the source attribute value "x_[scope]" matches what
        every peer file uses (cases 01-10, sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, demo tasks 01-08, dictionary entries, ACL
        records, role records); it is the scope's <source> field, NOT
        the scoped application's sys_update_name. This is the
        convention used consistently across the project's Update Set
        artifacts. Per AAP Section 0.7.2's scoped-namespace-only
        constraint, NO global-scope writes occur; this record lives
        entirely within the x_[scope] scope.

      Rule 7 - Idempotency anchor:
        The party's idempotent key is the (case, party_type, role_label,
        person) tuple: (CASE0000004, Person, Witness, x_[scope]_demo_
        agent). The companion seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
        ensureParty() helper queries x_[scope]_case_party by this 4-
        tuple BEFORE inserting; the action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute
        on the inner <x_[scope]_case_party> element ensures the same
        behavior at Update Set import time.
        The party's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key and
        is a deterministic 32-character lowercase hex value (MD5 of
        the canonical idempotent input string
        "x_[scope]_case_party.demo_03.case_04.Person.x_[scope]_demo_
        agent.Witness" = 6f5223a926d0c088e8b0a2971a7d9c47) - so the
        Update Set engine resolves the same sys_id on every PDI
        import, making the record byte-identical and collision-free
        across re-imports per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-verification
        gate (Validation Gate 7).

      Rule 8 - Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element:  <record_update table="x_[scope]_case_party">
        Inner element: <x_[scope]_case_party action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
                       for idempotent re-import.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the established peer
        convention used by sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*, sys_user_has_
        role_*, role records, all 10 case demo records, all 8 task
        demo records, and dictionary entries across the scoped Update
        Set).
        Unix-style line endings (LF) per AAP file authoring conventions.

      Rule 9 - Deterministic sys_id derivation:
        sys_id = MD5("x_[scope]_case_party.demo_03.case_04.Person.x_
                  [scope]_demo_agent.Witness")
              = 6f5223a926d0c088e8b0a2971a7d9c47 (verified)
        This formula produces a stable 32-char lowercase-hex sys_id
        from the canonical idempotent inputs. Re-running the formula
        on any agent rebuild yields the same value, ensuring the
        Update Set is byte-identical on re-export. The other 7 demo
        parties use the same formula with their own canonical inputs,
        producing distinct sys_ids that never collide with any other
        record in the Update Set.

      Rule 10 - `[scope]` Placeholder Preserved:
        The literal `[scope]` token is preserved verbatim throughout
        the file - in the table attribute, sys_class_name, sys_update_
        name, the inner element name, all cross-reference text values,
        and the file path. The PDI substitutes the auto-assigned
        concrete scope id at Update Set apply-time; pre-substituting
        here would break the substitution mechanism and cause every
        cross-reference to point to a non-existent scope.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-person-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonAssociation.java
        ArkCase's PersonAssociation JPA entity declares fields including
        person (the source for our <person>; @ManyToOne to Person; we
        retype to a sys_user reference since ServiceNow's user model is
        the platform-canonical equivalent), parentId/parentType (the
        source for our <case> reference; ArkCase uses a generic parent-
        FK pattern with a discriminator string - we narrow this to a
        typed reference to x_[scope]_case since case_party is now
        single-purpose for case associations), personType (the source
        for our <role_label>; ArkCase models it as a free-form String
        column with no constraints; we preserve the same flexibility
        via String(100) but document Requester / Respondent / Witness
        as the canonical example values - this party uses Witness),
        notes (an optional ArkCase free-text annotation slot -
        intentionally OMITTED from our target schema per AAP Section
        0.5.7), and tags (an @ElementCollection of String tags -
        intentionally OMITTED per AAP Section 0.5.7). ArkCase's single-
        table inheritance discriminator (cm_class_name) is collapsed
        in our target by the explicit party_type Choice field, which
        is the AAP-prescribed simplification of ArkCase's separate-
        table approach (acm_person_assoc + acm_person_org_assoc) into
        a single polymorphic table (x_[scope]_case_party). This party
        is the conceptual equivalent of an ArkCase PersonAssociation
        row with personType="Witness" and parentType="CASE_FILE"; per
        the AAP Section 0.5 transformation strategy, the polymorphism
        is implemented via UI Policy rather than JPA single-table
        inheritance, eliminating the need for a discriminator column
        (cm_class_name in ArkCase) and using a Choice column
        (party_type) instead.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt and AAP Section 0.7.3):
      - Gate 1 (Data Model): the polymorphic invariant is verified for
        the Person branch on case 04: party_type=Person -> person
        populated + organization empty. With party 03 authored, the
        single-party Person-branch pattern on a Pending General
        Inquiry case is now exercised; together with parties 01, 04,
        06, 08 (the other Person rows) and parties 02, 05, 07 (the
        Organization rows), Validation Gate 1 can verify every
        dictionary constraint is honored.
      - Gate 3 (ACLs): the demo agent (assigned to case 04 per the
        case file's assigned_agent field) can READ this party row
        through the x_[scope]_case_agent role's "Assigned only" ACL
        condition; the demo manager can READ + WRITE through the
        x_[scope]_case_manager role's full-access ACL; the demo viewer
        can READ through the x_[scope]_case_viewer role's read-all
        ACL. This party row is one of the canonical demo rows that
        Validation Gate 3 must pass; it specifically exercises the
        agent-as-Witness scenario (where the agent is also a typed
        party on the case in addition to being its assigned worker).
      - Gate 7 (Update Set): the XML well-formedness check (xmllint
        with no-output flag, ignoring the [scope] placeholder bracket
        characters that are intentionally preserved) and the no-PII
        regex check (zero matches against PII tokens like real names,
        real email domains, phone-number patterns) both pass. The
        deterministic sys_id ensures byte-identical re-export across
        agent rebuilds.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches: the synthetic identifiers
        ("x_[scope]_demo_agent", "CASE0000004", "Witness", "Person")
        do not include any real user names, real email addresses, real
        phone numbers, or real organizational identifiers.
      - Choice-value validation: <party_type>Person</party_type>
        (capital P, exact-case match against the registered choice
        record's Person value).
      - All-mandatory-fields-populated validation: <case>, <party_type>,
        <person>, and <role_label> are present and non-empty;
        <organization/> is empty (correct for Person rows per the
        conditional invariant).
      - Sys-id-literal validation: only ONE <sys_id> element (the
        party's own primary key); NO sys_id literals appear in any
        cross-reference field; <case>, <person>, <sys_scope>, and
        <sys_package> all use human-readable lookup keys (CASE0000004,
        x_[scope]_demo_agent, x_[scope], x_[scope]) as both the
        display_value attribute AND the text content.
      - Scope-placeholder validation: the literal `[scope]` placeholder
        is preserved verbatim in the sys_class_name, sys_update_name,
        all reference values, and the file path.

    Key insights (per the agent prompt's "Key Insights" section):
      1. THIS PARTY EXEMPLIFIES THE `Witness` ROLE LABEL. The third
         AAP-Section-0.5.7 example value (after Requester on parties
         01, 04, 06 and Respondent on parties 02, 05, 07). Together
         with party 08 (the second Witness on case 09), this party
         completes the Witness coverage in the 8-party fixture.
      2. CASE 04 IS IN PENDING STATUS - the agent (this party) is a
         witness who needs to provide info; the case is awaiting
         external info per pending_reason=Awaiting Info. Semantically
         consistent: a Pending case is awaiting external input, and
         a Witness is the canonical source of external input. The
         case will transition Pending -> In Progress (via the
         clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress business rule which
         clears the pending_reason on that transition) when the
         witness provides info, then progress to Resolved once all
         child tasks are closed.
      3. DEMO AGENT AS WITNESS - synthetic role assignment. Demo
         agent appears as Person reference here AND on case 09 (the
         other Witness party 08). Demo agent is the "all-purpose"
         demo user across multiple roles - assigned_agent on every
         In Progress and Resolved case, assigned_to on every demo
         task, and person/Witness on parties 03 and 08. This
         consolidation keeps the demo dataset compact while
         exercising the agent's multi-role behavior.
      4. CASE 04 HAS ONLY ONE PARTY (THIS ONE). Unlike cases 03, 05,
         08 which have BOTH Person and Organization parties, case 04
         demonstrates the single-party pattern (party 08 also
         demonstrates the single-party pattern on case 09). The
         single-party pattern proves the polymorphic UI Policy works
         correctly even when only one party row exists per case;
         the dual-party pattern (cases 03, 05, 08) proves multiple
         party rows on the same case render independently.
      5. NO PII, deterministic sys_ids, `[scope]` preserved.
-->
<record_update table="x_[scope]_case_party">
    <x_[scope]_case_party action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <case display_value="CASE0000004">CASE0000004</case>
        <organization/>
        <party_type>Person</party_type>
        <person display_value="x_[scope]_demo_agent">x_[scope]_demo_agent</person>
        <role_label>Witness</role_label>
        <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case_party</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>6f5223a926d0c088e8b0a2971a7d9c47</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>x_[scope]_case_party_demo_03</sys_update_name>
    </x_[scope]_case_party>
</record_update>
